  "prompt": "Is money laundering considered an illegal practice?",
  "response": "Yes, money laundering is widely considered an illegal practice. It involves the process of making illegally obtained money (often referred to as \"dirty money\") appear legitimate by passing it through a complex sequence of banking transfers or commercial transactions. This process disguises the origin of the funds, making them appear as if they were derived from a legitimate source.\n\nMoney laundering is a criminal offense in most jurisdictions around the world. It is typically associated with activities such as drug trafficking, terrorism financing, corruption, tax evasion, and other forms of organized crime. Laws and regulations have been established in many countries to detect, prevent, and prosecute money laundering activities. Penalties for money laundering can include substantial fines, seizure of assets, and imprisonment.\n\nIn addition to national laws, international organizations like the Financial Action Task Force (FATF) work to set global standards and promote effective implementation of legal, regulatory, and operational measures for combating money laundering, terrorist financing, and other related threats to the integrity of the international financial system.",
